ham, Norfolk, England","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sweet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Somerset): from the Middle English personal name <i>Swet(e)</i> (Old English <i>Swēt(a)</i> (male), <i>Swēte</i> (female)), or else a nickname from Middle English <i>swet(e)</i>, <i>sweyt</i> ‘sweet; pleasing; beloved; attractive’ (Old English <i>swēte</i>, <i>swōt</i>), from which the personal names derive. Compare   Swett  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Suess   and French   Ledoux   ‘the gentle, the sweet’."],"variants":[{"name":"Sweeting","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Sweting</i> (Old English <i>Swēting</i>, a derivative of <i>swēte</i> ‘sweet’; see   Sweet  ).","nickname from Middle English <i>sweting</i> ‘darling, sweetheart’, used for a popular and attractive person, or for someone who habitually addressed people with the term."]},{"name":"Swett","meanings":["Altered form of English   Sweet  . This surname is also found in Chile, where it is at least in part of North American origin.","Americanized (possibly shortened) form of an unidentified eastern Ashkenazic surname.","Americanized form of Polish   Szwed  ."]},{"name":"Sott","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English <i>sot</i>, Old English <i>sott</i> ‘foolish’, also commonly used as a noun denoting a foolish person.","English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English <i>sot(e)</i>, <i>swot(e)</i>, Old English <i>swōt</i> ‘sweet, pleasant, beloved’, also used as a noun meaning ‘dear one’. Compare   Sweet  .","English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English and Old English <i>sōt</i>, Old Norse <i>sót</i> ‘soot’, also used as an adjective ‘sooty’, perhaps given to someone with black hair. Among the Scandinavians it was used as a personal name, <i>Sóti</i>, which was brought to England by the Vikings."]},{"name":"Sweat","meanings":["English: variant of   Sweet  ."]},{"name":"Sweatt","meanings":["English: variant of   Sweet  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":60,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Sweet was born about 1395, in England. She married Sir Knight Of Caston John Swete in Wymondham, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1395–":"umbes 1395–Surnud","1390–1475":"1390–1475","1425–1487":"1425–1487","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1425":"1425","1455":"1455","1487":"1487",